# Firebase Configuration

This file should NOT be committed to version control!

## Web Environment Variables (VITE)

For web apps (Vite), create `.env.local`:

```env
VITE_FIREBASE_API_KEY=your_api_key_here
VITE_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-project.firebaseapp.com
VITE_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
VITE_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-project.appspot.com
VITE_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=your_sender_id
VITE_FIREBASE_APP_ID=your_app_id
VITE_FIREBASE_MEASUREMENT_ID=your_measurement_id
```

## Node.js Environment Variables

For Node.js apps, create `.env`:

```env
FIREBASE_API_KEY=your_api_key_here
FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-project.firebaseapp.com
FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-project.appspot.com
FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=your_sender_id
FIREBASE_APP_ID=your_app_id
FIREBASE_MEASUREMENT_ID=your_measurement_id

# Application
NODE_ENV=production
LOG_LEVEL=info
```

## Security Notes

1. **Never commit .env files** - Add to .gitignore
2. **Use environment variable restrictions** in Firebase Console:
   - Set API key restrictions to HTTP referrer
   - Restrict access to specific domains only
3. **Enable Firebase security rules** in firestore.rules
4. **Use Service Account** for backend operations (not client SDK)

## Getting Values

1. Go to Firebase Console: https://console.firebase.google.com
2. Select your project
3. Click Settings icon → Project Settings
4. Find your configuration under "Your apps"
